snippet.textDisplay:
Man, high-end phones are going to be costing like 2 grand in the near future! It's pretty insane how high the cost of these phones have become, although for what they are capable of doing ( Basically a small computer, phone, and nice camera all in one) it isn't too unreasonable I suppose! I just remember not that long ago, a $700-$800 phone seemed very expensive lol. Although, both Samsung and Apple, as well as other companies, do have more budget-friendly options, but I always go for the newest flagship phones, although I always skip at least one generation, and don't get a new phone every year because usually the upgrades from one gen to the next are very minimal! For example, I saw no point in upgrading my iPhone 6s Plus when the 7 came out, or my X when the XS came out. Two or three generations seem to be when I personally feel it's actually worth upgrading.


The specs of the S20 Ultra are certainly very impressive, but realistically how much of a difference will they make in regular/everyday use? The biggest improvement is likely the camera, but who really needs 100X zoom and 8K video on a phone camera? lol I mean most people haven't even really caught up to 4K yet! At the same time, I would like to pick one up because even other than the impressive camera, it does have some nice features, and I am looking to replace my second phone line which was a Note 9 that I gave to my grandma when her phone broke. I was planning on just going with a Note 10 Plus because I really liked the Note 9, even though the iPhone 11 Pro Max and previously an iPhone X was my primary phone. I just like and am more used to iOS over Android, but I started to really enjoy the Note 9! Although, I was hesitant at first after the Note 7 disaster! I had unfortunately got two of those, and ended up getting stuck with two S7 Edges instead ( Which I absolutely hated using)! Since I never really used the S Pen, the S20 seems like the best option, except for when it comes to price...but hey, I expect the release of the S20 to drive down the prices of the Note 10's, so I may be able to pick up a great deal! Although, I am into computers/tech kind of stuff very much, and the S20 Ultra looks great with the best specs any phone has ever had. I may just have to wait a bit longer to replace the Note 9 and get one of these, but that price tag is a bit steep! Even with installment payments, I believe it would be approx. $47 a month for the 128 GB version! Although, with expandable storage, I guess that's not a huge issue. I certainly don't need one, another Note 9 would work just fine for me, yet I can't seem to help myself lol, but if I can get a great deal on a Note 10 Plus, I am just going to go with that, which is still a very nice phone! I am really curious to see what Apple does next though, since Samsung has very much surpassed them as far as specs go. I'm hoping the iPhone 12 is a massive improvement, even though I won't be getting one, but will wait until the next generation more than likely. I like my iPhone 11 Pro Max, but really other than a larger screen than the X, along with a better camera, I don't notice a huge difference in performance. Overall still worth the upgrade though, but this S20 is really going to be competing against the iPhone 12 more so than the 11 Pro I believe which was released about 5 months ago. Although, Samsung likely has plans to release a new Note around the same time the new iPhones are released I would imagine?


Anyways, good video! Thanks for the comparison.

snippet.textDisplay: Build quality-wise, the iPhone is superior in every way. That frosty back glass is brilliant. What Samsung has is the generic FP magnet glossy crap everyone has been putting in their phones for a while now. Then there's the stainless steel which is undoubtedly more durable. So yeah, nothing special about the Samsung. I wish the Android world had a champ who could be on par with what Apple offers right now. I don't care if someone comes with arguments as to why this material is not so good because, blah blah. But this is my point of view.
snippet.textOriginal: Build quality-wise, the iPhone is superior in every way. That frosty back glass is brilliant. What Samsung has is the generic FP magnet glossy crap everyone has been putting in their phones for a while now. Then there's the stainless steel which is undoubtedly more durable. So yeah, nothing special about the Samsung. I wish the Android world had a champ who could be on par with what Apple offers right now. I don't care if someone comes with arguments as to why this material is not so good because, blah blah. But this is my point of view.
